le in counts/categories.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure is tied to real git initial-state behavior (unborn HEAD, command exit behavior) observed via CLI execution. MOCK-MISS: stubbing repo APIs can hide real error codes/messages from git in empty repos. REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: needs real repo on disk and CLI/process path to verify no crash and correct empty output. Rejected higher levels: no AI/ML decision quality and no multi-step agent pipeline in behavior text.","test_description":"Initialize a real git repo with zero commits, run the CLI subprocess, and assert it exits successfully and prints a valid empty structured report.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.71,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is end-to-end correctness against real git history semantics across multiple change types; failures often arise at module handoff (history extraction→classification→report rendering) with real repository state. REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: synthetic fixtures can drift from true git history behavior and hide counting errors. System is minimum to validate actual history via CLI on a real repo. Rejected higher levels: behavior does not involve model output quality or agentic sequencing.","test_description":"Construct a real repo history containing known numbers of adds/deletes/renames/modifies across commits, run CLI subprocess for the target range, and assert reported counts exactly match independently computed ground truth from gi